---
import ChapterEntry from '../components/blocks/ChapterEntry.astro';
import Prose from '../components/blocks/Prose.astro';
import Diagram from '../components/blocks/Diagram.astro';
import VignettePlaceholder from '../components/blocks/VignettePlaceholder.astro';
import ChatPlaceholder from '../components/blocks/ChatPlaceholder.astro';
import type { Chapter } from '../data/chapters';

type Props = Chapter;
const { number, title } = Astro.props;
---

<ChapterEntry
  chapterNumber={number}
  title={title}
  lead="One module gets live access to the full system at runtime."
/>

<Prose>
  <h2>The privilege gap</h2>

  <p>
    Every module in Amplifier receives the Coordinator (the registry where
    modules are stored) once: at mount time. The module uses it to register
    itself, and then the Coordinator reference is gone.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Orchestrator is the exception. It receives the Coordinator again, at
    runtime, <em>every time it's called.</em> This means the Orchestrator can,
    at any moment during execution, reach into the registry and access any
    module: the Context Manager, every Provider, every Tool, every Hook Handler.
  </p>

  <p>
    No other module can do this. A Provider can't look up which Tools are
    available. A Tool can't check which Provider is being used. Only the
    Orchestrator has a live connection to the full system at runtime. This is
    by design, not by accident.
  </p>
</Prose>

<Diagram
  src="/diagrams/reasoning-loop.svg"
  width="wide"
  alt="The OODA loop: Think, Act, Observe, Decide — with the Orchestrator at center"
  caption="The OODA loop: THINK → ACT → OBSERVE → DECIDE, cycling with the Orchestrator at center."
/>

<Prose>
  <h2>The loop lives outside the kernel</h2>

  <p>
    The agent loop — the "think, act, observe, repeat" cycle — is not in the
    kernel. It lives in an Orchestrator module. The Orchestrator decides what
    context the AI needs, which provider handles each request, how tool calls
    are handled, and when to stop.
  </p>

  <p>
    A different Orchestrator module could implement a completely different
    strategy: parallel provider calls, multi-step planning, debate between
    models. The kernel would not change.
  </p>

  <p>
    At the end of every turn, the Orchestrator returns a <strong>plain string</strong>.
    Rich data — token usage, tool history, thinking blocks — exits through hook
    events. The string is the public response; hook events are the telemetry.
    Add instruments without changing the engine.
  </p>
</Prose>

<VignettePlaceholder
  width="wide"
  rationale="The 4-phase cycle is hard to grasp from text alone. Animation of the loop with each phase lighting up and data flowing would teach faster"
/>

<ChatPlaceholder
  prompt="Have a question about how the orchestrator drives the agent loop?"
/>
